ecisions, and transforming researchers' relationships to communities for equity and mutual benefit. The book offers a critical synthesis of relevant research in many fields, outlines the main steps in conducting community-engaged research, evaluates the major research methods used, suggests new directions, and addresses overcoming institutional barriers to scholarship in academia. The coauthors employ an original framework that shows how community-engaged research and environmental justice align, which links research on the many topics treated in the chapters-from public health, urban planning, and conservation to law and policy, community economic development, and food justice and sovereignty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental justicezUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aResearchzUnited States. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBaptista, Ana Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoj Lopez, Floridalma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowmani, Zsea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastillo, Celestina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Vera L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCommodore, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia, Jeanyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJules, Malaya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLucero, Julie E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMares, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4